[When she was the Louisiana State public health epidemiologist, the late Louise McFarland and I would have many discussions about human cases of eastern equine encephalitis (EEE) in Louisiana. While we had plenty of equine cases, human cases were far less frequent, and if the patient was hospitalised they recovered well. I think that in 30 years there was just one case that went home with permanent damage, no deaths. Our mutual opinion was that it probably reflected the year around presence of mosquitoes here. A frost merely buys us 7-10 days of mosquito freedom, and we can have winters with no frosts. And thus we probably have plenty of sub-clinical EEEv exposures. Put another way, the risk of severe human EEE cases is possibly proportional to the climatic severity of the local winters. Our problem is persuading the horse owners to vaccinate their horses each spring against EEE and WEE (western equine encephalitis). We routinely see deaths of unvaccinated horses. An unnecessary and expensive tragedy.

Maps of North Carolina can be seen at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3504235,10595 and http://geology.com/county-map/north-carolina-county-map.gif. Cumberland County is in central North Carolina, in the SE quadrant of the state. - Mod.MHJ]
